{{Nihongo|'''Kosaku Inaba'''|稲葉 興作|Inaba Kōsaku|January 16, 1924 – November 16, 2006}} was a [[Singapore]]-born Japanese businessman, former president of [[Ishikawajima-Harima Heavy Industries]] Co., head of the Japan Chamber of Commerce and Industry (1993–2001) and second president of [[Nippon Kaigi]] (1998–2001).<ref name=JapanTimes>{{cite news|title=Obituary: Kosaku Inaba|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2006/11/30/business/obituary-kosaku-inaba/#.VoyEOPFcT5k|accessdate=6 January 2016|work=The Japan Times Online|date=30 November 2006|language=en-US}}</ref> He was a graduate of [[Azabu High School]] and [[Tokyo Institute of Technology]]. He joined the Ishikawajima Shibaura Turbine Co. in 1946. In 1962, the company merged with Ishikawajima-Shibaura Seiki Co. and Shibaura Sewing Machine Co. and changed its name to its current one. Inaba rose through the ranks as board director, managing director and senior vice president before becoming president of the company in 1983 and chairman in 1995.<ref name=kotobank>{{cite web|title=Inaba Kōsaku|url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E7%A8%B2%E8%91%89%E8%88%88%E4%BD%9C-1055525|website=Kotobanku|publisher=Asahi Shinbun|accessdate=6 January 2016|language=Japanese}}</ref> He was a recipient of the [[Order of the Rising Sun]].
