{{Infobox magazine | title = Manhattan, inc. | logo = | logo_size = <!-- default is 180px --> | image_file = Manhattan-inc-cover.png | image_size = | image_alt = | image_caption = August, 1988 cover | editor = {{unbulleted list|[[Jane Amsterdam]] {{small|(1984–1987)}}|[[Clay Felker]] {{small|(1987–1990)}}}} |editor2 = | editor_title = <!-- up to |editor_title5= --> | previous_editor = | category = | frequency = Monthly | format = | circulation = 115,000 | publisher = [[D. Herbert Lipson]] | paid_circulation = | unpaid_circulation = | circulation_year = | total_circulation = | founder = | founded = | firstdate = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | finaldate = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | finalnumber = | company = | country = | issn = 0748-6472 | oclc = }} '''''Manhattan, inc.''''' was an American monthly magazine published in New York City. From 1984 to 1990 it profiled the rich and powerful figures of New York City's business world, and featured stories by prominent freelancers such as [[John Seabrook]], [[Ron Rosenbaum]], and [[Gwenda Blair]].<ref name=Carmody/><ref name=Kasindorf>{{cite magazine|title=The Amsterdam News|first=Jeanie|last=Kasindorf|magazine=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|date=May 30, 1988|pages=40–44|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=teMCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40}}</ref>
''Manhattan, inc.'' was founded by [[D. Herbert Lipson]], owner of ''[[Philadelphia (magazine)|Philadelphia]]'' and ''[[Boston (magazine)|Boston]]'' magazines. The first issue debuted in September, 1984, edited by [[Jane Amsterdam]], who previously edited ''[[New Times (magazine)|New Times]]'' and ''[[The American Lawyer]]''. In 1985, after only four issues, it received a [[National Magazine Award]] for General Excellence.<ref name=Sullivan>{{cite book|first=Colleen|last= Sullivan|editor-first1=Sam G.| editor-last1= Riley|editor-first2=Gary W. |editor-last2=Selnow|contribution=Manhattan, inc.|title=Regional Interest Magazines of the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Wb_1YI0zSxIC&pg=PA140|year=1991|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-26840-3|pages=140–143}}</ref> Amsterdam and eight other staffers departed in March 1987 over a dispute with Lipson about editorial integrity.<ref name=Kasindorf/><ref name="Lipson, Inc.">{{cite magazine|last=Diamond|first=Edwin|title=Lipson, Inc.|magazine=New York Magazine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KeUCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA28|date=27 April 1987|pages=28–34}}</ref> [[Clay Felker]], the founding editor of ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'', replaced Amsterdam as editor.<ref name=Sullivan/> Under Felker, the magazine became "less sassy, less critical, and more featurish in tone"<ref name=Sullivan/> (''[[Spy (magazine)|Spy]]'' magazine wrote Felker "helped dull the magazine's cutting edge").<ref name="Spy 1990">{{cite magazine|last=Urquhart|first=Rachel |title=Voyage to the Bottom of the Newsstand|url=https://archive.org/stream/bub_gb_zMJ8RrL7CxoC#page/n61/mode/2up|magazine=[[Spy (magazine)|Spy]] |date=November 1990|pages=60–67}}</ref> It suffered financially after the [[October 1987 stock market crash]], and ceased publication in July, 1990, merging with the men's lifestyle magazine ''M'' to become ''M, inc.''<ref name=Carmody>{{cite news|last1=Carmody|first1=Deirdre|title=Like the 80's, Manhattan, inc. Ends|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/06/22/business/like-the-80-s-manhattaninc-ends.html|work=The New York Times|date=June 22, 1990}}</ref>
Calling it a "[[Yuppie]] Anti-Yuppie Magazine," writer [[Brian Morton (American writer)|Brian Morton]] described ''Manhattan, inc.'' as "aimed at a young, hip audience of people who see through the hypocrisies of the business world even as they want to make their way in it."<ref name="Morton 1989">{{cite book|last=Morton |first=Brian|editor-first=Jim|editor-last= Sleeper|title=In Search of New York|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k78wjoTW-iQC&pg=PA169|year=1989|publisher=Transaction Publishers|isbn=978-1-4128-2612-9|pages=169|chapter= The Banker's Red Suspenders: Looking at Yuppie Anti-Yuppie Magazines}}</ref>
